1 year from the Eastern Iburi Earthquake: Water is secured even during power outage.
In response to the total power outage (blackout) caused by the Eastern Iburi Earthquake in September last year, measures are being taken in the condominiums in Hakodate City where the water cut off.
According to the city's Bureau of Water and Sewerage, seven condominiums were installed in one year after the earthquake, and a "watering plug" was installed that could produce water even after a power outage.
There are over 400 condominiums and private housing units in the city that supply water with a "passenger tank type" that can be cut off when a power outage occurs.
The house's water supply system is broadly divided into two types: the "passenger tank type" for water once placed in the receiving tank located underground or on the roof, and the "direct connection type" for watering directly from the city's water distribution pipe to each door.
Even if the water pipes are not damaged, electric pumps that pump water from the water tanks to each door will not be able to run due to power outages, and each door will be cut off.
