"Korea wishes to return to GSIMIA" U.S. Undersecretary of State (Asahi Shimbun) - Yahoo!
U.S. Undersecretary for the U.S. Undersecretary of State for South Korea and Japan, Mr. Napper, in response to an independent interview with the Nikkei Shimbun at the residence of the U.S. Ambassador to the United States in Tokyo, said "I hope Korea will reconsider and come back to the decision to destroy Japan and Korea's comprehensive military information protection agreement (GSOMIA) which expires on November 23."
It is unusual for U.S. officials to refer to the reconsideration of GSOMIA's destruction.
GSOMIA is based on the agreement between Japan, Korea, the United States, and the United States, and the ROK to share missile launch information.
In August, Korea announced that it would destroy the agreement with Japan, and if it expires, the framework for protecting military information will collapse.
Napper argued that "without GSOMIA, we cannot effectively respond to crises."
"There is time to expire," he urged the return of Korea.
The joint flight training conducted by Churo in July over the Sea of Japan was also recognized as "the first time in history."
He pointed out that the recent deterioration in Japan-Korea relations "damaged the national interests of the United States."
"There is no intention of intermediation," he said, "We will play a positive role to fill the gap between Japan and Korea."
