Sakura Ebi in the Growth Process PT in Shizuoka City, and 290 meters deep | Shizuoka Shimbun at Ess
Sakura shrimp, born this year, was successfully photographed in the deep sea of Suruga Bay.
The Yuhi Sakura Ebi Project, a project of the Ocean Industry Cluster Council led by industry, academia, and government officials in Shizuoka City, succeeded in photographing Sakura Ebi, which is believed to have been born during the spawning season this spring and summer, at a depth of 290 meters in Suruga Bay.
The video of the growth process is valuable, and the concerned parties want to lead to the elucidation of the ecology of sakura shrimp, which has many mysteries.
The photograph was taken near the bottom of the sea about 1 to 5 km off the coast of Kamahara district, Shimizu Ward.
A total of 300 were confirmed in 17 minutes.
In the daytime, the traditional knowledge that sakura shrimp in the deep sea form a certain flock at the bottom of the sea was re-established.
The adult body is about 40 mm long and the individual shown is about 23 mm long.
The spawning season was identified by matching data from different seasons of freshly caught sakura shrimp.
Detailed analysis is requested by Fujitsu Software Technologies and Shizuoka Industrial Technology College, which make up the team.
Keisuke Mizuno, Project Leader, said, "I want to capture the living figure of the individual in the growth process, including fry."
