Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries (Gifu Shimbun Web) - Yahoo!
On March 27, the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries released a draft amendment to the Anti-Defection Guidelines to prevent the spread of Ton cholera, a disease that has been transmitted to livestock, in order to prevent the infection.
The target area is to select nine prefectures, including Gifu Prefecture and Aichi Prefecture, where pigs and wild boars have been identified.
Live pigs and fertilized eggs that are vaccinated are restricted to the region, but distribution outside the meat and processed foods is permitted.
After making public comments (an open call for opinions) to the general public, we aim to complete the procedure in October as soon as possible.
By using vaccines and allowing extraterrestrial distribution such as meat, it is no longer a "clean country" certified by international organizations and may affect pork exports.
Since the outbreak of September last year, Japan has been on hold for a while.
In the revised plan, the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries set up the "Recommended Vaccination Area" based on the opinions of experts regarding areas with high risk of infection from wild boar to pigs.
The target prefecture creates a "vaccination program" that summarizes the scope, time, number of heads, and how to proceed with vaccination.
Seven other prefectures, including Saitama, Toyama, Ishikawa, Fukui, Nagano, Mie and Shiga, are recommended for vaccination.
When the guidelines are revised, the region will review the situation and make decisions extremely once again.
The movement of inoculated pigs, semen, fertilized eggs, corpses, and excreted objects, in principle, is restricted to the region.
With regard to meat and processed products, it is not targeted based on the cost of distribution restrictions and the impact on farmers, and it virtually accepts distribution outside of the country.
In order to prevent viruses from spreading, we will thoroughly process food waste.
He also advocates the safety of the inoculated pigs and works to prevent harmful rumors.
The revised guidelines were compiled at an expert meeting held on the same day and confirmed at the meeting of the Anti-Defection Control Headquarters.
In the future, opinions and public comments to prefectures will be conducted until October 7 and new guidelines will be enforced.
