Leading-edge art in the world Okayama Art Exchange opens in the center of the city: Sanyo Newspaper Digital | Sanyo Digital
People around the classroom who will be the stage for a video work depicting the future 3,000 years later
The International Art Exhibition "Okayama Art Exchange 2019" held every three years in the center of Okayama City (organized by the executive committee of the city, prefecture, etc.) opened on the 27th.
Along with the mysterious title "IF THE SNAKE If Snake," 18 artists from 9 countries enjoy cutting-edge art created by art fans both in Japan and abroad.
This time, the second time following 16 years, we have invited French artist Pierre Yuigu as artistic director to develop works that utilize Okayama's climate and local resources.
Approximately 40 films and three-dimensional works will be shown at 13 locations, including the former Uchiyama Shimo-ko (Marunouchi, Kita Ward, Okayama City) and the prefectural Tenjinyama Cultural Plaza.
Prior to the opening ceremony, a small opening ceremony was held, and about 100 people attended.
Mr. Masao Omori, Mayor of the Executive Committee, and Mr. Yasuharu Ishikawa, General Producer of the Executive Committee, made a tape cut, saying, "The works that stimulate intellectual sensibilities and stimulate imagination and creativity are scattered and become an exhibition that attracts attention from the world."
The families and children who visited the school immediately saw a snake-shaped robot that responds to the sound of the surrounding area in the dohyo of the school yard, and walked around the school building that changed into the stage of a video work depicting the world 3,000 years later.
I enjoyed the art that came to the world.
In his first year of high school in Tokyo (15), when he was traveling with his father, he said, "It's interesting to have a work that takes advantage of the atmosphere of the old school building, and I can imagine the time that flows into this place."
It is closed on November 24 (the following day for national holidays).
Hong Kong rally in five years of rain umbrella movement tens of thousands, aiming for a general election | Shizuoka Shimbun at es
Five years have passed since the "Amembrance Movement" started, and people gathered at the meeting hall = 28th Hong Kong (co-operation)
[Collaboration with Hong Kong] A rally of tens of thousands of people was held in the park near the Hong Kong Government Headquarters building of the Admiralty, which had the largest base of the demonstrators, on the 28th of May since the 2014 large-scale demonstration "Ambrella Movement" which sought democratization of the Hong Kong administration election.
Some young people occupied the main road around the venue and threw fire bottles into the government building.
As protests started with the amendment of the Fugitive Ordinance continued, the participants renewed their resolve to fight until the "true ordinary election" which was not won at the time.
In June, the protests were more than 112 days after 79 days of the Umbrella Movement, and the demands of the demonstrators expanded to "five major demands" such as electoral reform.
Ibaraki Kokutai Opens today 28th|Saga Shimbun News|Saga Shimbun
The 74th National Sports Festival "Ikiiki Ibaraki Yume Kokutai 2019" will be held on 28th.The general opening ceremony will be held at Kasamatsu Sports Park Athletic Stadium in Hitachinaka City, Ibaraki Prefecture, and the 11-day heat battle will start until 8 October.
About 400 athletes and directors participated in 33 competitions, excluding those held before the exhibition.
The prefecture ranks 43rd in three consecutive years until last year, but last year it rose to 33rd.
This year, we are aiming for the first half of the 20th place.
In the pre-event competition held by the 16th, the Saga Women's High School of Gymnastics Boys and Girls of Gymnastics and the Seinen Women and Boys' Girls of Gymnastics won 6th place and played.
In each competition, we aim to advance to the top.
At the opening ceremony of the general opening ceremony, 83 players, directors, and officers of the headquarters marched on the 40th entrance, and a rugby boy, Kugo Ishikawa (Saga Koko), was the flag bearer.
On the first day, wrestling, table tennis and karate are held.
